This auction is for real tree camouflage version.Akdal MKA 1919Page issuesThe Akdal MKA 1919 is a gas operated, semi-automatic shotgun that resembles the M16 rifle and mimics the layout and placement of some of the controls. It was created by Turkish company Akdal Arms. The MKA 1919 uses a conventional gas-operated action which is located around the support tube that runs below the barrel. The return spring is also located around the same support tube which is concealed by an enlarged polymer handguard. The MKA 1919 barrel can be quickly removed from upper receiver. To charge the rifle, the charging handle on the receiver must be pulled. The upper receiver is manufactured from an aluminum alloy while the lower receiver, along with pistol grip and shoulder stock, is manufactured as one piece from impact-resistant polymer. Akdal MKA 1919 semi-automatic rifle has a 5-round detachable box magazine. It has a bolt release identical in location and function to the one on the M16. Manual safety also duplicates M16-style being located on the left side of the receiver above the pistol grip.[1] Standard sights include a front post installed on the M16-style removable base and a detachable M16A2-style carrying handle with built-in diopter sight. On the upper receiver, an integral Picatinny rail exists which will accept detachable carrying handle or optional red-dot or other optical sight attachments.

title: For Sale:  FS: Taurus PT138/PT132 Millenium .380 / .32acp
postcontent: For sale is an excellent condition Taurus PT138 Millenium .380 ACP (9x17mm) pistol with an extra .32acp PT132 slide and barrel assembly. One gun shoots both calibers. This is a striker fired locked breech pistol with second strike capability (can drop the striker again by simply pulling the trigger again should the first strike fail to ignite a hard primer). Anyone can operate it but it's a great choice for anyone with low hand strength or recoil shyness.  The locked breech doesnt require a heavy recoil spring so operating the slide is very easy, and the slide velocity is lower than a blowback gun so it also tames the already low recoil of the .32 and .380 calibers. People that have shot this gun comment that it feels like shooting a .22 pistol, but of course it makes much bigger holes. In it's niche it stands out the only high capacity locked breech compact .380 available, ideal for carry or plinking and much easier to grasp and control than a subcompact Glock 42 or S&W Bodyguard. The ample grip, low recoil and light weight make this an easy gun for novices to shoot quickly and accurately without flinching.I purchased the extra slide with the original intention of converting it to .32 NAA but a surprise baby has canned that experiment. Pistol includes both .380 and .32 ACP upper assemblies, 2x 12 round .380 magazines and 3x 10 round .32acp magazines. The .380 upper extractor and barrel have been carefully polished to enhance feeding. Prior to polishing these parts FMJ ammunition fed fairly reliably, but HP or FP ammunition would hang up every now and then. After the polishing it's a completely different gun though, it's impossible for me to induce a feed failure with FMJ, FP, or HP ammunition. Feeding is so smooth now that .380 will even feed reliably feed from the .32 acp magazines, and while I wouldnt use the .32 magazines while carrying .380 it does gives you a few more magazines to practice with at the range.Also of note is the Taurus security lock integrated into the gun. Should you wish to disable the pistol while storing it, use the included Taurus security keys to twist the locking cam 180 degrees and the firing mechanism is disabled.I value this gun at $250 for the pistol w/2 .380 mags mags, and $175 for the .32 upper with 3 .32 mags. postcontent: Manufactured by Winchester between 1898-1899. Not a reproduction. 12 ga4+1 CapcityFactory Wood Stocl32" in BarrelOriginal Engraving on receiverLever Action Another highly innovative John M. Browning design, the Model 1887 shotgun is one of the most unusual actions ever made by Winchester. Production began in May of 1887 and it ended in March of 1899, with a total production of just 64,855 guns. The Model 1887 was replaced in June of 1901 by the modernized Model 1901. The Model 1887 shotgun is a lever-action rolling block design, chambered in 12-gauge 2 ⅝” and 10-ga 2 ⅞” black powder shells only. All Model 1887 shotguns have an elegant “WRA Co.” monogram engraved on the left side of the receiver frame, and were case color hardened.
